data.enText: to use a particular set of facts or ideas in order to form an opinion that is considered valid for a different situation

data.chText: 仅从一个事例进行归纳的做法是愚蠢的。
data.enText: It would be foolish to generalize from a single example.
to make a general statement about sth and not look at the details

data.chText: 对穷人一概而论是危险的。
data.enText: It is dangerous to generalize about the poor.

data.chText: 扩大…的运用；将…类推到（较大的范围）
data.enText: to apply a theory, idea, etc. to a wider group or situation than the original one

data.chText: 这些结论不可能推及全国。
data.enText: These conclusions cannot be generalized to the whole country.

tr: become systemic and spread throughout the body
example: this kind of infection generalizes throughout the immune system

tr: cater to popular taste to make popular and present to the general public
bring into general or common use
example: They popularized coffee in Washington State
Relativity Theory was vulgarized by these authors

tr: draw from specific cases for more general cases

value.boxr_value: in BRIT, also use 英国英语亦用 generalise

value.def: If you generalize, you say something that seems to be true in most situations or for most people, but that may not be completely true in all cases.

example.ex: 'In my day, children were a lot better behaved'. — 'It's not true, you're generalizing'...
example.tran: “我们那个时候，孩子们要比现在听话许多。”——“不一定，你只是在一概而论。”

example.ex: It's hard to generalize about Cole Porter because he wrote so many great songs that were so varied.
example.tran: 科尔·波特写了这么多风格迥异的优美歌曲，要对他进行概括并不是件容易的事。

value.def: If you generalize something such as an idea, you apply it more widely than its original context, as if it was true in many other situations.

example.ex: A child first labels the household pet cat as a 'cat' and then generalises this label to other animals that look like it.
example.tran: 孩子会先把家中的宠物猫称为“猫”，然后将其他像猫的动物都称为“猫”。
